A Place to Sit in
Greenpoint, Brooklyn

Illustrations and story by Rachel Win

New York is known for it's chaos, it's noise, it's frantic energy; but you what happens when you need that momentary respite form it all?

NTC Department of Transportation records over 2100 benches across the city, and growing, and as a long time resident of Greenpoint, I wanted to map some of my favourite spots that have helped me fall in love with this city over and over agian.

Greenpoint is a 2.754 mi area situated at the most northern point of Brooklyn. There's a big expanse of water front to the neighborhood, looking over both Long Island City and Manhattan.

First, lets look at the parks in Greenpoint.
To explore the benches around Greenpoint, you can hover your mouse over the bench icons.

Since the majority of the neighborhood is surrounded by water, there's plenty of sitting areas to enjoy the river view.

The ferry stations shut down at two points in greenpoint, which has made for great spots to walk out over the river and get a closeup of all boats, planes and people.

My favourite, and lesser known spot for perching is at the top the Pulaski bridge. Here you have a great view of manhattan and Long Island City and below it is the Newton Town Creek nature walk, a slightly hidden gem that runs between two toxic sites along what's thought to be one of the most polluted water ways in the USA! Somethig of a perfect metaphore for quiet sitting spots in the city of New York.
